{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530064"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:02:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:02:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14487"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14487"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.18,0.14,0.62,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55991"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7182"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41540"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3620"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4367"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43533"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55991"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for preconception counselling. She has a medical history of essential hypertension diagnosed five years ago and is currently well-controlled on lisinopril 10 mg daily. She does not take any other regular medications. She and her partner have been trying to conceive for the past two months. On examination, she appears well with a blood pressure of 130/80 mmHg. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management regarding her antihypertensive medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discontinue lisinopril without replacement","Continue lisinopril until pregnancy is confirmed","Switch to amlodipine immediately","Switch to methyldopa immediately","Continue lisinopril for the first trimester"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is taking an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor, \u003Cstrong\u003Elisinopril\u003C/strong\u003E, for essential hypertension and is actively trying to conceive. ACE inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnancy due to their association with fetal renal damage, oligohydramnios, and other congenital abnormalities, particularly when used in the second and third trimesters. There is also some evidence of increased risk of congenital malformations with first-trimester exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eswitch to methyldopa immediately\u003C/strong\u003E. Methyldopa is considered one of the safest antihypertensive medications during pregnancy, with a long history of use and no known adverse effects on the fetus. Other safe options include labetalol and nifedipine. It\u0027s crucial to make this switch before conception to avoid any potential fetal exposure to ACE inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing lisinopril until pregnancy is confirmed\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended because by the time pregnancy is confirmed, the fetus may have already been exposed to the medication during early organogenesis. This approach carries unnecessary risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinuing lisinopril without replacement\u003C/strong\u003E could lead to uncontrolled hypertension, which itself poses risks to both the mother and the developing fetus if pregnancy occurs. Uncontrolled hypertension in pregnancy is associated with complications such as preeclampsia, fetal growth restriction, and placental abruption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to amlodipine immediately\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best choice in this scenario. While calcium channel blockers like amlodipine are generally considered safe in pregnancy, methyldopa or labetalol are typically preferred as first-line agents for chronic hypertension in pregnancy due to their longer safety record.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing lisinopril for the first trimester\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated. Although the greatest risk of fetal abnormalities occurs with second and third-trimester exposure, there is still a potential risk in the first trimester, and it\u0027s best to avoid ACE inhibitors entirely during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to changing her medication, this patient should receive counselling about the importance of early and regular antenatal care, as women with chronic hypertension require close monitoring during pregnancy due to their increased risk of complications such as preeclampsia and fetal growth restriction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ACE inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnancy due to risk of fetal renal damage and other congenital abnormalities.","Women with chronic hypertension should transition to safer antihypertensive medications before conception.","Labetalol, methyldopa, and nifedipine are considered safe antihypertensive options during pregnancy."],"references":["Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Hypertension in Pregnancy Guideline 2023 [Internet]. Updated 30 June 2023. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2023/06/SOMANZ_Hypertension_in_Pregnancy_Guideline_2023_Updated_30.6.23.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41540"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14487"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41540"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T08:09:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T08:10:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7182"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55991"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group